Question 3

1 point

The median age of ten people in a room is 50 years. One 40-year-old person leaves the room. What can we expect will happen to the median age for the remaining nine people? Do we know the median age of those nine people; if so, what is it?

Answer: The median will remain the same because it is resistant to changes in the data. The median of the remaining 9 people will be 50. ### Question 4

1 point

The mean age of ten people in a room is 50 years. One 70-years-old person leaves the room. What can we expect will happen to the mean age for the remaining nine people? Do we know the mean age of those nine people; if so, what is it?

Answer: The mean age will decrease because it is not resistant and a larger number was removed. The new mean age of the remaining 9 people will be 47.78.

Question 5

1 point

The mean age of ten people in a room is 50 years and the standard deviation is 3 years. One person leaves the room, and both the mean and the standard deviation become larger. What do we know about the age of that person?

Answer: That person was younfer than 50 years old.

Question 2

5 points

I hypothesize that providing free child care at election voting stations will increase turnout among families with young children. Design an experiment to test this hypothesis. Describe any shortcomings your experimental design may have.

Answer: There would be two variables. IV would be child care, DV would be voter turnout. The sample would be families with young children and adults who are eligible for voting. The project would be carried out in two randomly selected counties. The control group would be the county with no childcare, the control would be the county with free childcare at polling stations.Treatment would be randomly assigned to one of the two counties. I would create advertisements informing families of free childcare at voting stations and randomly select the families within the treatment county that would receive them. I would then compare if families were more likely to vote after they had knowledge of free childcare at voting stations.

Potential problems could include that those families that were randomly selected to receive the advertisements would spread the message via word of mouth, affecting the process of randomly selecting families.

Part D

Describe the direction and strength of the relationship between renewable energy use and wealth.

cor(log(renewables$gdp_per_cap), renewables$renewables_use, use = "complete.obs")
[1] -0.6070358

The relationship is negative and weak for the non logged data. It is negative and strong when looking at the logged data.
